        <chapter>
          <title>Taxis vs. Uber: the European Strikes</title>
          <paragraph>In June 2014 thousands of cab drivers took to the streets for large-scale protests over the famous ride sharing company, Uber. Protests in London, Madrid, and Berlin over the use of a mobile app to handle payments had forced a gridlocked stop. With all the commotion, however, Uber was seeing substantial gains in the App Store: the Uber app for iPhone had been climbing the App Store charts in major European countries immediately after the protests were announced.</paragraph>
          <paragraph>The App Store’s fast reaction to the protests meant even more new users for Uber. These events worked in their favor: remarks from Uber executives showed they embraced the protests as a way to display the convenience and functionality of the service.</paragraph>
        </chapter>
